**Clinical Reasoning:**
This infant presents with recurrent petechiae, ecchymoses, and epistaxis without trauma, suggesting a primary hemostatic defect. Despite a markedly elevated platelet count (>450,000/mm³), there is an increased bleeding time, pointing toward impaired platelet function—consistent with von Willebrand disease (VWD). The absence of thrombocytopenia rules out thrombocytopenic causes like Bernard-Soulier or immune-mediated disorders. The normal PT and INR suggest intact secondary hemostasis, excluding deficiencies in vitamin K-dependent factors. Large platelets on smears and preserved platelet numbers support a defect in vWF binding or release, typical in VWD.

